    AWS set of the RDS and EC2 connection  

•	Open the aws acnt and search for rds (Relation database )  go to  Database and select create database.
Easy create → Quick start, good for learning or dev/testing.
•	Standard create → Full control, best for production or when you need specific configurations.
         Select the option easy create and select the database 
       •  If you’re just learning / practicing MySQL & RDS → Free tier (db.t4g.micro) is more than enough.
•  If you’re building projects or want realistic testing → Dev/Test (db.r7g.large) is a good middle ground.
•  If you’re deploying a real production app with users → Production (db.r7g.xlarge) is the safest
•  Learning / Practice → Use Self-managed and set a password you can remember.
•  Testing with security in mind → Use Auto-generate password but store it safely (e.g., in Notepad/Password Manager).
•  Production → Go with Secrets Manager, since it’s the most secure and allows rotation.
Create Database

Verify RDS Status
•	Go to AWS Console → RDS → Databases.
•	Make sure your DB status is Available.
1.	EC2 (Amazon Linux) to RDS MySQL Connection
Now lauch  EC2 server with  RDS (Mysql port for Security G ) 
Connectivity:
o	VPC: choose same VPC as EC2.
o	Public access: No (recommended), unless testing from laptop.
o	VPC Security group: select/create one.

